but I work with XMPP and Android, so here is my answer: As Ryan already stated, an handover from one mobile cell to another is almost always transparent to the TCP stack on Android devices.
this are typical GSM/UMTS <-> WiFi switches, which will cause the TCP connection to become unusable by the XMPP client.

on Android the standard XMPP library that clients use - besides using their on proprietary one - is (a)Smack: Clients that use (a)Smack with an default configuration will not notice an connection change in a timely manner.
